FINALLY got to take out a @porsche Cayenne Turbo GT for a drive that was freshly traded into @porscheofthemainline a few days ago…and damn, this thing is a massive weapon of destruction, word order being intentional. This thing grips, snarls, BOOGIES like it has no business doing as a pretty full sized SUV.
 The handling of the GT is probably the most interesting thing about the car as the steering is programmed really fast. If you move your hands just a little on the wheel, the response is instantaneous and pretty drastic…even more than the outgoing Lamborghini Urus. You’ve really got to pay attention in this thing as a sneeze will send you half way into the other lane. The flipside of this is you feel like you could thread this monster through a tight road and completely forget you’re in an SUV. This car must rip chunks of tarmac out in its wake, and there’s no understeer here to speak of or lean at ALL and Id wager it damn near keeps up with a 991 gt3 on almost any back road with the torque this German bean-tank has at its disposal. 
  Moving to the engine, this thing has a nuc reactor with turbos attached to it and the pops, bangs and turbo wooshes on full loud when you’re thumping on the car are addictive, and you WILL contribute to global warming as you keep dipping into a mile deep trench or torque and eco-nightmares over and over in disbelief of how rapid the GT is. 
  Addressing overall comfort..the GT is prettttty damn stiff, but in the base shock setting honestly isn’t that punishing, I’d be able to ride in it daily and not have an issue, but press the suspension button for the lower and more sporty settings and yeah, you’ll feel the ant you just crushed hurdling down to Costco for economy sized Tums containers your passengers will need because of your hooning about 😂. 

Overall, I have to say the GT is mean, meaaaannn sportscar thinly (metaphorically) veiled as an SUV, and if you buy one, or this one…just know that while you won’t be able to relax cruising down the road, you’ll be grinning ear to ear like a total buffoon.  #porsche #sportmade #cayennegt #porschecayenne #porscheclub #sportscartogether #porschemoment #porschelifestyle

I’ve managed to put a couple hundred miles on the 992 GT3 Touring so far, and admittedly…it’s a PHENOMENALLY fun car. Overall, what really impresses me the most about the 992 GT3 is how versatile it seems to be, while also bringing in enough driver involvement and excitement to really make it a hard to beat package if you’re shopping for an “all in one” 911. 
  To start with the the heart, the 4.0L motor is still the same gem it was in the previous 911.2 gen though I do find the tone with the ITBs to have a cool resonance that really does sound KILLER out of the @akrapovic muffler, which is about the perfect level of loud for a sport purpose car at least to me. I’d say it’s maybe 10 percent louder perception wise, but it does seem to round out the tone a hair compared to the last stock 992 gt3 I drove. It’s going to be a SAD day when these motors leave us, whenever that is. 
  Moving to the 6 speed trans, this car really does have a sweet gearbox. It’s extremely easy to use in any perceivable situation, though you absolutely need to give it extra revs from a total stop or you’ll risk a stall (yes, I did stall!) The throws are pretty short and the stick itself is short and compact (this is only a good thing in a car, otherwise embarrassing 🤣). The reverse gate is way stiffer than any 911 gear box I’ve ever driven though, which is fine just different, and the car does need to be warmed up before the off clutch first gear throttle tuning gets smooth (can be a little jerky after it’s been resting for hours until heat gets into the car #becauseracecar. 
  Chassis-wise, aside from this car being absolutely huge feeling, this car handles like no other 911 before it, the front end grip still shocks me, and in the rain it’s so communicative that you know how many little asphalt beads you’ve slid across when turning in quickly on a wet road. The ride quality…I have to admit, feels softer/better tuned than the wing car I drove in California and I have no idea why…it really is supposed to be the same (I have the same seats and tires as the gt3 wing car I drove as well and the wing car was at LOWER pressures to boot!) *Continued in comments*

Had another phenomenal drive day in the Touring. As far as continuing impressions, in a strange way this car kind of reminds me of my e46 m3 (manual) I had back in 2006. Aside from the colors also coincidentally matching, both of the cars could go from pretty comfortable (albeit sport purpose for sure) cruising cars to incredibly fun, exciting and legendary back roads rippers should you find yourself on a set of such backroads. I think one of the greatest parts of the 992 gt3 t in manual is you don’t necessarily need to set out to have a “drive” in order to really enjoy the car…the same was true in my e46 m3 and that really increases the enjoyment level I constantly have in the car. Additionally, the 18 way seats with heat are absolutely great for this cars purpose for me, and I wouldn’t enjoy this car with buckets in the same way as they just aren’t as easy to get into and out of when running those daily errands etc. Also on the ease of use theme, it’s really nice not having to really plan out drives to cater to cars unique attributes that can provide difficult on some routes re ride height or just operational use. The 992 is pretty much fine with everything save moon cratering and you don’t get the same “ick” feeling going down a road that’s not exactly perfect as one would in maybe a Mclaren, Mc20 or especially CGT or 918. Needless to say. I’m really loving the GT3 T as an overall car as well as sports car. Thanks to @ferrariphl , I finally a 296 GTB on the road for a few minutes for a quick review. Overall, within the context of new cars, Im pretty impressed what the 296 GTB offers in one package. It’s one of the first Ferrari’s I’ve been in that actually feels like a wholistic entity vs an engine attached to a gearbox attached to a chassis etc etc. I got in the car and I aside from some of the new style electronics, felt super comfortable in it instantly…no acclimation necessary. 
  Overall, the most whoa thing here is just how ridiculously/ludicrously fast the 296 GTB is. Not sure if that’s a good thing though as you’ll be doubling any speed limit without even banging redlines and one only has so many points on their license. Impressively, I don’t feel aside from the torque being impressive the hybrid unit acting separately from the motor which I definitely can feel in my 918. This. Car. HAULS. Not only that, but the transmission is really sharp and the paddles have a much tighter/shorter travel than F car paddles of the past which I like. The thing also sounds MAD good…proper noises. 
  Moving to the chassis, hey, @Ferrari has really made this thing exploitable…get too into the power and the car will step aside (830 hp rwd can do this) but the chassis response is so natural, catching it and continuing to thread the car where you want with its light steering is cake, and you really feel where the front is. Also, refreshingly…the 296 doesn’t feel like a heavy car when shoving it around, which is really just a rare feeling for a car that has a hybrid motor that puts down real power vs the Mclaren artura that ads sub 100 hp and is smaller to begin with. I have to say it’s impressive. 
  Overall…Im impressed with the 296 and can see why it’s effectively sold out even with its somewhat mammoth price when loaded up. It’s plenty comfortable, rocket ship fast and does look pretty cool outside of the showroom. While it may not be as much fun to me as hammering a 430 Scud or 360 Challenge Stradale around for a brief drive, it makes a real case for a modern supercar daily driver that would probably scare most sh1tl3ss on a track to boot. #ferrari #296gtb #newcar

Not going to sugar-coat anything here, the GT4RS is the most special, exciting modern Porsche I have ever driven on the road. Honestly, I put the experience of driving this gt4rs up against my CGT and 918 more than I do most of the 911 lineup…though it’s mid-engine setup does lend itself to that kind of categorization admittedly. 
  I have to get this part out of the way, I’m completely enthralled with the way the sound of this car envelopes you with a blanket of GLORIOUS motorsports sounds. The inclusion of the intake noise at the back of your head is the difference btw watching an IMSA race on tv vs being in the actual car, on the track. It opens up another sense of occasion that I’ve only experienced while being in ACTUAL race cars, most recently the gt4 clubsport a few months back…yet this is even BETTER. The closest experience after this is the 918’s exhaust pipes behind your head but this is still somehow different. In a world of quieter and quieter cars, this sound explosion is worth nearly any amount of money to be able repeat on command…and 8-9k is nearly new religion creation worthy, I’ve never heard anything like it. 
  Chassis wise, the gt4rs is simply alive. This car ignites your inner Daytona driver…you find this chassis allows you to play with the car on a road the way Ali played with his opponents. Light and nimble inputs reward you with direct and sure footed responses, and when you punch the accelerator abruptly because you’re a spaz and the rear end jiggles, you catch the car with your fingertips and flat out melt at just how perfect the gt4rs flies down a curvy road.
 Moving to the transmission, this is simply perfection. There’s something about the tuning here (does seem like the 991.2 rs’ box) is unbeatable for pdk. It’s fast, but somehow it’s just a little more eventful each shift and the gearing for a backroad is perfect.
 Addressing the interior…honestly, I love the old school vibe in the 4rs…it’s comforting and lets you focus on the drive. 
  At the end of the day, this car is the automotive equivalent of an orgasm…it’s hard to not get addicted and fall hopelessly in love every time you drive it. #porsche #GT4RS #perfection

I had the pleasure of being invited by @rufnorthamerica (congrats on the new branch by the way @rufsince1939 @victorgomeziv !!!) to drive the carbon bodied RCT EVO restomod that Ruf offers currently and had an awesome time in it. The RCT EVO has a 3.8L single turbo that puts out about 430 HP and these can be done in both narrow and wide body, but for some reason…I REALLY dig the narrow body. This car was done in @porsche ‘s Oak Green metallic with a brown interior and definitely looks the business (it’s also for sale), that aside driving impressions…
 I will probably do a comparison post vs my singer tomorrow, so I’ll keep this one more brief…but the defining characteristic of the RCT evo is solidity. This car drives like a Porsche product that’s been perfected vs it’s own thing (vs the 50th anniv CTR which seems to be its own thing completely). The 3.8l T motor is GLASS smooth, taking off with the heavy but butter clutch with ease and sails to its redline like smooth jazz…power comes on with a whoosh when the turbo spools up and the Ruf rushes forward with a mission. Shift the perfectly smooth 6speed gear box and the power just keeps on coming. 
  Chassis wise, the Ruf is DEFINITELY still a 964, but the suspension has been tuned to handle the power perfectly yet not sacrifice any ride quality at all…you could easily road trip this car. Throw the RCT evo around a bit and I just feel SOLID.  You know exactly what this car will do at all times, I’d LOVE to get in a groove with it on a track. The steering remains plenty weighted as well, so for those who love that feel, you’ll love the RCT. Brakes wise, everything works perfectly with the steel rotors (ceramic optionable) and there’s not much to report here other than it stops rather well (good thing with all that power). All in all, there is so much quality in this build that I’m absolutely impressed with @rufsince1939 and their resto department, this is a gem. Oh, and of course we had to stop at Big Cheese pizza, because I’m cheesy and pizza and Porsches go together like well…pizza and Porsches 😂😂😂. What a fun time @victorgomeziv !!!! #porsche #ruf #luftgekühlt #rufporsche

Ruf RCT EVO vs Singer Classic (SQN pic @drewphillipsphoto )
I mentioned in my post yesterday after taking the RCT evo out compliments of @rufnorthamerica that I would write a little comparison of these two as they are the most similar in product offering save one being na and one being turbo as far as what’s done to the cars from a similar starting point. 
  To start out, right off the bat I can tell you the two cars drive extremely differently and had different goals in mind. The @rufsince1939 RCT EVO is more of a “how do we make this 964 the best 964 we can” ethos to me. There is zero doubt from the moment you get in this car that it is, obviously a 964. The cars dynamics follow that directive as well. But compared to a stock, rather bland but entertaining 964 (sorry 964 guys, I love a 964 but a stock version isn’t lighting too many fires from a dynamic standpoint), the Ruf turns everything up exponentially. The suspension is perfectly tuned for performance comfort, rewards pushing but doesn’t punish you for doing it. The car has stability that you wouldn’t think a 430 hp single turbo car should have, and the Ruf feels levels more “solid” than a stock car, granted a built in roll bar will do that to a car. The Ruf feels special in that you feel like you’re in a 964 with an OEM plus quality level. All these things make it a phenomenal car, and a killer 911. 
  Now to the @singervehicledesign classic, where the Ruf feels like a 964, the Singer classic feels like another thing entirely. Where Ruf wanted to perfect the 964, Singer wanted to perfect a driving experience surrounding a 911… the Singer is more of a wild/emotive experience, from its steering feel through its motor and trans characteristics…it feels racier, buzzier and a little more flavor forward than the more Germanic approach Ruf takes to the RCT Evo builds. I feel like I’d put down faster times on a track with the Ruf, but I’d be laughing more in the Singer, with its lighter steering wheel dancing through the hands as you manage the thinner tires grip levels constantly on track. To end, both of these cars are brilliant, and would compliment eachother in a collection...LOVE. #porsche #restomod

This car was in @caranddriver a while back and has had plenty of coverage around the media world, so it’s awesome to experience it first hand.

The boost sounds build up and the car simply ROCKETS forward but in a really smooth and predictable way, but with an added dash of potential serial killer thrown in for excitement…Dexter anyone?The tuning here was done VERY well and the motor pulls incredibly strong through redline literally eating cars within a half a mile of it faster than you can say “oh mein gott”. Connected to the RUF gearbox, you make fast work of the gears and the trans is a pleasure to use and heel toe downshifting is a BREEZE with the throttle response. On the Highway, this thing is a full-on beast, on a track it’s got to be lighting hair on fire fast. 
Suspension wise, I’m not sure what it’s on but it’s totally complaint for a near race car build and in corners and with the wide body work and tires, it sets in and def gives a LOT of confidence, something that’s nice for a 700 hp car to give you. The wing fills up the rear view mirror and you 100 percent feel like a balls of steel racer from the 80s in the race buckets with harnesses and interior half cage. Got to take out a @ferrari Pista for the first time thanks to @meritpartners and I have to admit, this is a Ferrari I’m a big fan of. To me it’s like a sexier bodied 911 Gt2rs but with just a little more on road fan-fare (it is Italian after all) and a little less grip (which leads to said fan-fare). I’d definitely still rather be in a GT2RS on a race track but for the road, oof I may actually prefer this. The pista has a really, REALLY solid feel and doesn’t have any of the differential/throttle sensitivity the 458 Speciale did which I really didn’t gel with (yes, Im in the minority here and aware). I felt like I could throw the pista around anywhere and it would give me the feedback needed to continuously deploy ludicrous amounts of horsepower for anything I could see fit, and having the will power to not set the drift angle setting to huge and send it around every corner is real. Also props to Ferrari for their TC in this car, aside from being necessary it’s brilliant…it lets the car get loose and you give your inputs but if it’s a dumb input, it smacks it down like an Americanized dish of spaghetti and meatballs handed to an Italian chef. The steering is fluid and actually wonderful feel wise here. Im still a bit intoxicated by the car days later, even without a screamer sound given the sound robbing turbos though it doesn’t sound bad. This thing is a winner…and now has me thinking maybe sell the mc20 for one (plus a kidney)…thanks again Jonathan for letting me rip in this one that is currently available for purchase 👌. #ferrari #ferraripista #pista #italianstyle #italiangirl #italianfood #ferrariclub #ferrarif1 #topgear #atlanta

It’s official, the @lamborghini Huracan Tecnica is the best modern Lamborghini I’ve had…if you’re looking for one to use and keep, I’d say this is THE one. I’ve now been through an older lp610 AWD, a lp610 rwd, a Performante, STO and finally my current Tecnica (not to mention the Av. SVJ but different kind of car). The Tecnica really is the most amazing blend of each of the previous cars I’ve had but with a special X factor that really seals the deal for me. The most direct comparison is to the STO, which is a phenomenal car but just had a couple things that bothered me which the Tecnica solves. 
Starting with the suspension, the Tecnica takes a MUCH needed 15-20 percent off the stiffness of the STO. This car, make no mistake, is still SUPER stiff…even in base mode, but instead of it being what you constantly think about, it’s justtttt livable enough that it lets you enjoy what it’s capable of vs punishing you for taking it out every time. The front turn in is honestly just as good as I remember the STO being and both models are WAY better than the 610 rwd or performante are…and I’d say the rws programming in the T and whatever is going on in the front almost make it feel more direct than in the STO. The T is BRILLIANT here and the overall chassis feels like it’s straight out of a trofeo car. It’s epicly solid and tossable/threadable in a manner that reminds me more of a Porsche RS car than it has any right to be.
 Power wise, I don’t know what it is about the T but it feels peppier/more eager than the STO. This thing is FAST. It seems like it actually makes closer to 660-675 hp, and I don’t recall my STO feeling like that though I’m sure it’s the exact same. The transmission tuning is flawless, this is the best of the best of “neo-school” lambo powertrains pre hybridity to say the least. 
  Livability wise, the Tecnica is phenomenal. Save the stiffer ride, you can see out of the back and side windows so easily…the fake scoop in the STO drove me me nuts as it sacrificed your rear view so much. This is perfect…with the unique looks and best of it all in one package, I’m BEYOND in love with the Tecnica…its really the ONE. #lamborghini #huracantecnica

Took out the 91 3.3l 911 Turbo that @porschemainline currently has for sale for a quick ride as I’ve never actually been in a 3.3L before. Have to say, absolutely LOVE the way it drives…these turbos have a single turbo vs the twin turbo setup the 993 following the 964 got and it absolutely drives differently for it. Low end…well, yeah it’s a single turbo car for sure, you NEED revs for the power to come on here and you’ll find you want/need to use 1st gear into really slow corners if you want that torque well to be there, but that’s no sweat as this g50 box is perfectly smooth and the 3.3l revs pretty smoothly and quickly so rev matching isn’t a problem at all. Once you’re into power, this 91 turbo REALLY gets going nicely. It’s not “wow” power but it’s just perfectly rapid and engaging…you definitely want to chase as many gears as you can. 
Handling wise, this thing is such a fun mix…you’ve got more rear grip than you need and the front likes to float around a hair so you can adjust anything you want by playing with the throttle and having light responsive hands…and it’s perfectly predictable as any old 911 tends to be in that regard which makes spirited driving far more involved than in the newer cars with their much more sophisticated suspensions. The fact these turbos don’t have awd makes them noticeably more fun to me dynamically than the 993 tt that followed it albeit slower overall. 
My favorite thing about the 91 Turbo? The size…this car drives like a matchbox Vs it’s nearly twice as large feeling 991/992 siblings and when you’re in it, you’re a part of it…really something I wish we could get back in modern cars but don’t hold a lot of hope for, but ugh is it a BLAST when you get a go at a sorted one! #porsche #911turbo

A little bit out of left field, I saw that @jlrwestchester had a v8 d90 available on the lot and had been recently fond of the D90 platform in general post @carguy610 getting one. It’s a quirky, chunky little thing with strange proportions but something about it was just captivating…I asked @ryan_kahl at LR West Chester if I could take it for a little rip thinking that I didn’t really LOVE my last Defender v8 110 but this was worth a shot. The shorter 90 chassis paired with the v8 is a little BEAST to hurl down curvy roads. It’s outright grip is modest at best but the involvement factor, torque out of the corners and general silliness/rowdiness level absolutely won me over within a few short miles…I was SOLD. Pulled back into the dealership, thought about if I could live with the 2 Vs 4 door of my current Full-size RR and realized that no one’s been in the back of that car in the last 6 months. As the pic shows, I obv thought why not and went for it…meanwhile my 2023 530se Fullsized with 4800 miles will be avail there shortly and has been flawless to me if anyone wants a GOOD one! The guys at JLR West Chester took EPIC care of me yet again, and got me a killer deal (if you’re in the market for any defender, LMK and I’ll connect, they want to move before the 2024s come!). Thanks again guys, and @tony_piazza_ / Piazza family…flat out pumped to hoon around in this shorty rally-vibes SUV!! #newcar #landrover #defender #defenderv8 #suv #suvlife #landroverlife #landroverdefender #tuesdaymotivation #carsofinstagram

That’s me (insert “How I Met Your Mother” how did I end up here narration here) taking off in @redshift75 ‘s brand new DLS from pit lane at @weathertechraceway two days ago. The thoughts (curse words) and excitement (literally shaking) barely being contained by a seat belt, I head down to pit exit…DLS purring away as I do a few superfluous shifts to get a quick feel and turn the steering wheel back and forth as if to try and wake myself up to what must be a dream, I get on the hot track and squeeze the best pedal with my right foot which leads to instantaneously combusting in laugher/amazement/sheer childish joy. The sound, HOLY F-ing WOW x infinity…DLS HOWLS LIKE NO OTHER FLAT 6 EVER (yes, I’m screaming). I haven’t even gotten to turn in for t3 and Im having multiple moments. I turn the car to the right on a little bit of brake, load up the the car and throttle through, feeling every single little thing the track surface has to offer me before ripping to 9k rpm in 3rd gear, breathing on the brake pre turn kissing the rumblies towards turn 5…9k rpm shift to 4th, cry a little, 9k in 4th (cursing heavily), shift to 5 and then work down those two gears back to 3rd for t5 and launch myself up the hill…I could keep going and going, but long story short, DLS imprints every corner, straight and second you’re behind the wheel directly into your forever memory. The steering is firmer than Classic, but communicative to the point that it would make any couple in a relationship jealous (😂). You feed inputs into DLS, it feeds you 3 meals worth of information back. The chassis and composure instantly have you saying “oh, I can DEFINITELY brake later, push harder, get on throttle earlier…and when you do, it rewards you. The stability mid corner is INCREDIBLE , granted at a lane wide with fat rubber and not much weight it should be. Then when you get back on throttle, coax the back end around with your big toe and rifle up, and back down the gears to the next corner (omg, gearbox heaven) with the hollow shifter close to the wheel (CGT-ish)…I start to realize this may be the most extremely epic 911 ever. I couldn’t help myself with a little story-telling yesterday, so today is my more typical review of driving @redshift75 ‘s @singervehicledesign DLS. 
  There is NO question that DLS’ experience is dominated by what must be one of the most amazing motors in the history of motoring. The 4 valve 4.0l flat 6 that SVD and Williams designed is effectively the Carrera GT v10 of the aircooled world. It revs like no other aircooled car I’ve ever driven, pulls smoother than a professional pickup artist at a bar and makes sounds that would be banned in certain countries for public indecency. The smooth thrum to midrange trumpet to full on howl topped with a banshee shriek at red line progression of sounds as the intakes fill your brain with utter and complete witchcraft make chasing redlines the only thing that exists in life while you’re in the drivers seat. Coupled with the absolute gem of a short shifting, butter smooth 6 speed gearbox with perfectly spaced ratios and raised shifter barely inches from the steering wheel, this is a flat out auto god-tier combination that reminds me of my old 996 @flyinglizard_ms built cup car which was effectively a narrow body GT3R and it’s lightning fast shifts and insanely free revving 3.6 which revved to the same 9300 rpm redline DLS does…simply put, utterly amazing. 
  Moving to the suspension and chassis, SVD beyond nailed the mix of capability, feel and soul with DLS. This car was set up for the road and as such, provided a little lean and roll which really let you lean into the throttle and the back would just shimmy a hair and then set and grip BEAUTIFULLY even in second gear around T2 at WeatherTech. The chassis would then tell you exactly what it was thinking…and you can exploit its response around the grip limits with a delicacy that I don’t think exists in the standard car. If it were mine, I’d be dialing in a little more camber and stiffening it up a hair for the track, but mainly because this car reminds me SO much more of a motorsports car than a road car…but that would definitely sacrifice its street composure. 
Conclusion? This IS the CGT of 911s, and honestly…I’d trade my CGT in for one of these 🙃. #porsche

Now to address the question of how @singervehicledesign ‘s Classic (my car) and DLS compare which is something that I’ve been asked a bunch since the last couple posts. To start, SVD’s Classic and DLS provide two very distinct driving experiences…each designed at answering two different questions within the 911 world. Classic answers the question “what’s the best mix of 911 that could possibly be made to be used and enjoyed in every day (car enthusiast/nut case’s) life”. Classic is the car that you don’t have to think twice about grabbing the keys and getting in. Doesn’t really matter the road conditions, the weather or where you’re going, Classic is a no brainer. The operation of Classic is well…classic. It drives like a perfected 911 with every aspect of enjoying a 911 enhanced…gearbox full of feel and smooth, engine that’s lively and strong and a configurable suspension that’s easily suited to any road and still provides way better than average feel and performance vs any stock or normally worked aircooled 911. Classic is at home on the road, and HAPPILY flogged at the track…it’s simply the best all day 911 to me. 
  DLS answers a different question…”what is the most wild expression of aircooled na 911 that’s still enjoyable on a road, but at home on a track”. DLS doesn’t really want to plod along low speeds, the clutch more like my CGT…you have to be thoughtful and purposeful as far as when you want to move. You have to shift faster as the revs drop super fast, the steering weight is heavier and requires more effort and the cabin is WAY louder…the sounds of the gearbox, intake and pretty much everything else intrude into your space. When you’re in the mood and you can GET ON IT…there is nothing better. When you’re not, I could see it wearing on you…which is exactly what an extreme machine would do. The best part about Classic and DLS is they are perfectly complimentary…one for all days, enriching every drive, any time and one for days where you want your experience driving to be etched in your memory for life. I wouldn’t trade my Classic for a DLS, but oh lord do I want to add one…what a phenomenal set of masterpieces from SVD 🙌. #singervehicledesign

Given the freshly out @collectingcars x @harrismonkey video on the @tuthillporsche X @philipk852 911k…figured it an opportune moment to post these up. I’ve now had 2 passenger seat sessions in this car over the past 2 years…one by Richard Tuthill  and the other by Phil and each time I had a nearly irremovable ear to ear grin on my face and uncontrollable  bouts of laughter that honestly VERY few cars have ever caused in the same way. First off, this thing revs to 11k rpm…that’s ELEVEN THOUSAND just in case you thought you misread. On both of my rides the respective drivers kept it to 8-8500 ish but the sound that the 911k makes is absolute PURE race car aside from aircooled 911s this side of DLS from Singer don’t even rev that high. There are definitely short gears stacked in the 911k as the cabin was very busy with shifts the entire session, but what an event EVERY single time. 
Handling wise…this is effectively a tarmac rally car that weighs 1900 ish lbs…yes, this is the car you’ve been constantly asking Porsche if they could build with a modern car but I’ll tell you they can’t, however Richard can…no AC/no radio, no power steering, no real electric anything, reverse gear separated…the 911k is pure go, and zero superfluous show gold adornment aside. As such, pretty much anywhere Richard or Philip wanted the 911k, it went and with SPEED. Long LURID powerslides or fast apex kissing speed slides (it’s a rally car, this thing is set up for life after grip wanes and it shows)…the 911k is flat out insanity in a 911 shell. Philip tells me the road is ironically where it shines, but wow, is it a supernova on the track to say the least!!! Epic props to all parties involved here, the 911k is MENTAL and the ultimate skid mark machine, both on the tarmac and possibly on the seats pending how whoever is driving feels like making them 😅😂😂😂😂😂😂 #tuthillporsche #rallycar #porsche #aircooled #savethemanuals #getoutanddrive #luftgekühlt #porscheclub #porsche911 #california

I finally got to try the new @louisvuitton @lafabriquedutemps rendition of the Tambour that @arnaultjean and his team have been cooking up for the past couple years, and to say that I’m absolutely fascinated and impressed with what they’ve done is an understatement. I’ve always thought the 991.2 GT2rs was an incredible car. It’s obviously one of the fastest things you can drive on a road, or even a track with number plates but with the initial hype the prices were easily in the 500s for normal examples of the cars and tbh I didn’t really pay them much mind as that was just too expensive for me to consider at the time. Watching the market correct on them a bit, and then ultimately climb back and fully stabilize has made me take another look at this monster as a potential buy given how absolutely bonkers they are…while still being somewhat shockingly controllable unless you have the hammiest of hamfists (like you’d have to be a deli shop). With a few years gone by since I’ve driven one, after taking this car out…I’m still just completely bewildered @porsche figured out how to put 700 hp down on a road this well…while you may be doing SEVERELY illegal (hypothetically speaking) speeds, the GT2rs can get you there and confidently in a way Im not sure another car is able to do. The way the exhaust pops and barks when you let off the throttle on boost or shift (this pdk unit has my fave tune on it of all turbo pdk cars) is just mentally mean…it would be abuse if you didn’t love it so much, alas when you’re carrying hypothetically large speeds with “Thunderstruck” playing on the radio, you’re DEF enjoying that kind of abuse. The ride quality is totally tenable for normal roads and less springy feeling than a 992gt3…and inspires HEAPLOADS of confidence when you squeeze on the pedal of thrills out of a corner which is addictive, and likely an issue to a clean driving record. This gem 2RS manages to create a very unique experience against all of its other 911 variants in a way that really does have me think about trading something or adding it to the stable…and this guards red car (which is available, priced fairly and a GEM…message @rdsjesse for more info) is HYPER sharp. I have a feeling with the price of 992 3rs’ in the mid 400s, a few more people start looking at these like how I am now…as I have a feeling these just get more special over time. #porsche #gt2rs #porschegt2rs #porscheclub #porschelove #carshopping #supercar

This 1978 @rolex Sea-Dweller rail-dial is one of my favorite watches I own. I found this SD in Munich at @worldoftimede and kind of fell in love with it on the spot…there was a marriage of exceptional usage yet with some quite frankly magic features that captivated ze schnitzel out of me. The case was/is hammered and apparently belonged to a Turkish diver who obviously embraced the SD’s tool ethos to the fullest…yet also cared for this piece greatly when it came to its mechanical and internal condition. Purportedly unpolished, which I’m inclined to believe given the unreal thick/well shaped lugs,general originality of the piece mixed with its current state of wear (bracelet of similar wear/all parts correct date -wise) and bevels that still exist (though as with any vintage watch I wouldn’t bet my life on it), this SD also sports one of the best rail dials I’ve EVER seen condition wise. In juxtaposition to the exterior case and bezel… this Sea-Dweller presents stunningly well. I really loved the hunt for this watch (story is ALWAYS my thing) as I wanted a vintage something to remember that trip and I went to all sorts of places during my time overseas…and yeah, when I saw this, it was a “had to have” and the guys at Meertz World of Time were SO nice…it just made for a perfect little story of buying a really cool vintage watch when traveling, not to mention being able to withstand all the beer spilled on it during Oktoberfest with ease 😂. #rolex #vintagerolex #watchcollector #watchphotography #watchmania #watchesofinstagram #landroverdefender #wristshot #patina #watchcollection #vintagestyle

Given the general horological world’s collective timeline dousing with the Travis Scott  x @audemarspiguet ceramic perp collab…figured it would be a fitting day to post up a few shots of what I still consider the “best” (oof is that an icky word nowadays) ceramic perp that AP has done to date. This model, the OG ceramic perp and first watch like it to REALLY bring highly finished ceramic into the market creating the modern frenzy for the material is simply…how do I say the *perfect* (another icky word) higher horology daily and even travel watch. I still think the subtle grey dial with black subdials is by far the easiest to read and use of the ceramic perp lineup while being the most low key of the bunch. Truth be told, this model flies under the radar in all the good ways yet still manages to be REALLY special should you pay it more than one glance…a game in the details really. The hand-finished bracelet and case really have a black diamond-like glimmer to it when light pings off it’s angular surfaces yet doesn’t shout out for attention either.  Further more, and maybe the best part is this ceramic it’s imperviousness to scratches and normal wear which really make it a special watch that can also be well used without LOOKING well used over years (a god send for us OCD scratch haters). I’ve had mine since 2018 and if I give it a clean it looks BRAND new still. From a complications perspective, the perpetual is still the ideal horological information companion for a planner (can you tell I’m a Virgo #omgastrology ) given day, both in name and number, week and month indications…and when I tell you I use them all (aside from the moon-phase but we all know its a full moon when the crazies come out anyways #omgmoonsign), I mean it. Needless to say, it’s easy to see I’m still in love with this one and it’s accompanied me on more trips than any of my other watches by a mile, or 100k miles to be more accurate. Finally got to play with a couple of the new Oysterflex Daytona models and compare them to my now discontinued YG “Newman” dial variant (and yes, Im aware I need a ton of hand lotion, this cold weather zaps me 😂😂😂). First impressions…the newer reference reads as much “sharper” and more modern even though the gold ring around the bezel def has some 6263 vibes for SURE. I really like the shape of the new indices, but I do like the chunk of lume on my outgoing model’s indices when in the dark. Side by side, I’d swear the newer model (on the right) has a different gold blend than mine does as it really appears a full shade lighter to my eyes…closer to moonshine from Omega now. Is it from oxidation? Maybe…either way I really like how it presents. The new subdials appear more defined text wise and almost deeper looking as well with respect to the base part of the dial, which makes it feel more sophisticated yet punchy to me…if that’s a good or a bad thing is in the eye of the wearer. These traits also definitely make the former model present significantly more vintage…a little flatter and more faded. The one thing that’s the biggest difference though? Losing the red chrono second hand from the outgoing model to the new one is a real shame…it adds SO much character to the older one that I prefer the old model to the new one for this dial variant and wouldn’t want to swap them out as it’s the only one with that red hand across the lineup (or ever??) and it’s cool AF. That said, the white gold new reference I got to see was ABSOLUTE FIRE and blows the older WG references out of the water in in special factor. I’m def excited for the new “pikachu” variant which between that and the WG pictured are my faves of the new oysterflex models…not to mention the new glidelock clasp finally comes to this line, increasing wearability when dialing in the otherwise kind of non-exact sizing the normal strap sizing gave previously. To say I’m going to miss my 992 GT3 Touring is an understatement…a few pics from the first few days I had it, this is probably the car that caught me by surprise the most of the cars I’ve bought recently. Now you’re thinking, “wow, you were surprised that a new GT3 was great?? DUH” and in a sense you’d be right on, but let me explain. I knew I’d like this touring for all the reasons any Porsche GT product has been great in the past…great steering, great gearbox and that flat-6 which @porsche has tweaked to perfection…it’s an obvious winner. However, it was so something else, or multiple something elses so to speak that just made this car special. The 992 GT3 touring combines the best of usable and special all in one SUPER to drive package…and feels just normal enough with its lighter steering and wingless outline, yet also so exhilarating that it becomes the perfect “have your cake and eat it too” sports car boasting more front end grip than a dog who’s got your boxers and isn’t letting go. The Touring can slip anywhere and not get too much attention when short shifting the perfect 6 speed box, or you can rev the thing to 9k and have a mile’s worth of people turn their heads to see what race car is in the area…that sound literally doesn’t get old. I also fell in love with having the 18 ways in here…they made this car SO USABLE that I did just that, and often…which is kinda the point of a car with “touring” in its name. I was appreciative of every mile I did in this agate car and honestly…it brought me back to loving manual for modern cars again in a post pdk comfort-zone era which I had definitely fallen into. 
I was prepared to keep this car indefinitely, but the call of the ST and request that I trade this car in has brought me here…back to where this 992 GT3 T’s life started with me a year ago, and I’d love for its next owner to feel the same amount of joy for it that I had…and love every second, and every shift of it. Please reach out to @rdsjesse if you have any interest in a PHENOMENAL touring, and if you have a pdk car and miss that experience…this one is worth the trade. #porsche #992gt3 #gt3 #porschegt3 #savethemanuals #forsale #getoutanddrive

NWA…I finally bit the bullet on a Journe Octa S linesport model that I’ve been debating for a LOT of years. This is one of those watches that I’ve tried on about 438 times in the past and for some reason or another didn’t end up doing…yet, when I went to @watchbox today to check some watches out, I just couldn’t have it be time 439 trying it and not taking one home. There’s always been something special to me about these linesport models but I remember the years seeing them at a half, or even a third of the current values and maybe that just stuck with me creating a stubborn purchasing wall with them (even though I’ll pay considerably more for a car that’s far above original cost as a collector, go figure). Fast forward to today, and I’m realizing as I sit there that this is Octa Sport is maybe the most “me” watch that exists style and wear wise that isnt in my collection. The dark titanium case is as “on-brand” as it gets for me and is light AF.  The dark movement finishing is sublime, and a total contrast to the normal bright gold rotors and bright silvers found when glancing at a caseback, this movement doesn’t need to shout to be appreciated. The 42mm size of this case also wears like a 40mm as the lugs are effectively non existent and is easily the most wearable 42mm watch made imho…it doesn’t even make me wish it was smaller which I almost always do for a watch like this, but here it works and lets the numerals be that much more proportioned and readable at a glance. Additionally, I think I’ve seen 2 -3 people wear these in the wild over my entire collecting life…and I’m at the point that I appreciate the pieces that you rarely see out and I like the idea that at a watch get-together (aka Uber nerd fest events)…there’s probably not going to be another and lord knows I’m a sucker for individuality when it’s at all possible (looks at my Daytonas lovingly even still because yeah, I do ♥️ that stuff too 😂). This is definitely a watch I can see wearing for anything, anywhere and knowing it will slip under the radar while alerting other watch fans that I too am a “nerd supreme” as well. Going to love this one, thanks @briangovberg ! #fpjourne

My parents have always struggled finding me gifts for the holidays...I’m annoyingly specific with the things I like, and never expect anything from them to say the least (I find way more joy in figuring out fun things for them), but every once in a while they figure out something really, really cool as a gift, and they outdid themselves completely with this one. For a watch guy, there’s nothing cooler than when someone gets a watch from someone else that has a tie to the other person and their story vs just something else that the person receiving would buy on their own anyways…and this @hermes Arceau Squelette is exactly that kind of gift. I’ve always been appreciative of the Hermes watch line from an aesthetics point of view but never dove in given I’ve always got plenty of stuff on my list and honestly these haven’t been on it. My mother however loves the brand (lol, but really…the entire aesthetic is one of her favorites as even if recognizable in design, very few of her things from Hermes have any loud logos and she adores the quality) and she thought I’d enjoy something completely different to what I have. I can’t even say that I knew this model existed, though it’s apparently been around since 2020 and I have to say that after wearing it for the past 2 days, it’s kind of mesmerizing. This Arceau’s shining feature is it’s rather gorgeous fumé sapphire crystal showcasing it’s skeletonized movement…which, yes is a sellita movement, and yes some of you will roll your eyes here as it’s in theory not what you would ideally have in a watch at this price point. I’ve got to admit though, the way the light hits it through the smoked sapphire actually makes it look more mysterious than I’d ever believe such a movement could appear. Additionally, the numerals surrounding the dark sapphire portion of the dial are actually gorgeous font wise and bring an elegance to the otherwise mechanically oriented theme with this being a skeleton…I quite like them.  Case wise, this steel asymmetrical equestrian themed (hell if I know how but that’s what Hermes say) and wears perfectly in conjunction with the deployant buckle and gorgeous alligator strap. Bittersweet Symphony seems as fitting as ever for this moment…as  I am letting what I still believe is one of my favorite cars ever made go, yet for me is the right thing to do. The CGT, of which this was my third, is by all means a car that lives up to its reputation and beyond when it comes to an immense hypercar. It’s one of the most wild, pure and special machines to come out of the Porsche factory and the experiences and sensations it produces when driving it are for the most part without comparison. The problem? Honestly, I just don’t get to take it out much and with the stop drive with seemingly no end in sight as @porsche redevelops their control arm parts solution for each of these monsters has had this car simply dormant. A CGT does NOT want to be dormant…they need to be driven, loved and enjoyed. If you know me, you know I like driving cars more than just owning them. If I don’t get to take a car out at all, unless it’s a strict investment (the last CGT in black for instance)…I’d rather reallocate the money to something else that I know I’ll be using more, which in this case is the incoming 918 WP package in “my perfect spec” (yesterday’s story teaser), a few new toys being cooked up in Zuffenhausen (thanks to @porschemainline )and the incoming @rodemory and @singervehicledesign projects over this and the next few years. I’m finding more and more these bespoke restomod builds are really where my heart is for my future in car collecting when it comes to what I enjoy driving AND investing in the most. Whoever ends up buying this CGT from @grahamrahal @grahamrahalperformance will be getting an INSANELY mega driver, with completely fresh clutch, seals, cams, tires, @ohlinsracingautomotive suspension and an infinite amount of smiles whenever you take it out…and it deserves to be taken out as often and as passionately as possible. There’s really nothing in the world that compares to a CGT, and I’m going to miss the hell out of those sounds and feelings beyond. #porsche #carreragt #porscheclassic #porschlove #porschemoment #carsofinstagram #carswithoutlimits #carstagram #carphotography #getoutanddrive #cgt #savethemanuals #lovecars #carlifestyle

The first time I drove a 918 was after committing to this one from @grahamrahal and this was the day it landed a couple winters ago. I got in this stunning Rhodium silver with Garnett red 918 and took off with @rdsjesse down route 3. I made it maybe 1 minute 6 seconds before telling him that this was a SPECIAL car. I’ve never felt so at home and tuned in with a car that comes with Thor on meth after snorting crushed fruity pebbles sugar high levels of torque and a championship winning race car derived motor behind my head. I immediately felt like Superman, and the car was costume/cape/tights (now that’s a view)…it was so solid, SO fast yet so easy to feel everything out that it was doing my brain felt like Bradley Cooper’s character in Limitless after taking the brain power multiplying NZT (only without gaining Cooper’s charm, or face…sorry ladies ). I knew what this car was going to do before it did it and I was able to rocket this thing around roads like almost nothing I’ve ever been in. There ARE faster cars nowadays, both in a straight line and around a track…but damn if there isn’t an easier one to exploit. Anyone who’s been around chassis and engine tuning knows how unbelievable of a feat that is to accomplish while also having enough power to light up a city block during the holidays…lights and all. The 918 SHOULD want to kill you, you should be scared to rip around it in, you should feel the need to check that your will is in good order…yet none of this is the case (erm, maybe the will part as one could always choke on a Cheeto, but I digress). The 918 just makes you feel in control and out of this world when you’re behind the wheel…which is why I made the decision that I will always have a 918 in my collection. However, I wanted a weissach package car because I’m a nerd and while I love this non WP car with WP add ons, I really wanted a full fat WP car as a keeper…and thanks to Graham, I have that car coming. In the meantime, it’s time to say goodbye to this EPIC 918 that I’ve had for the last two years and hopefully someone else will feel the same as I did in it. #porsche #porsche918 #918spyder #porschelife #carphotography #carstagram #carsofinstagram

First drive impressions of the 991.2 Touring, and a little context to the 991 touring and R ahead…
 First off, this car just reaffirms that a manual 8500 rpm plus redline GT department flat-6 is my favorite car you can buy in the 200-300k range by a sizable long shot. It doesn’t matter which you choose, this setup just doesn’t get better for an enthusiast driver. Specifically, I find the 991.2 to have the best in car vibrations from the power train. The mid rpm engine sounds without the GPF filters def makes me hate that they ever had to do GPF in cars at all because it should be a sound crime. Alas, I’m going to have a NOT popular opinion here, but I prefer the TONE of both the 911r and the 992 to this one in the upper rev ranges…there’s just something a little more dense/pitched about the others that this one doesn’t quite nail to me but this is def a personal thing.  The 991.2’s transmission to engine pairing is just brilliant, a little less snick snick than the 992’s trans but also a little more fluid, and much easier to shift gracefully than the 992’s box. It’s a REALLY sweet thing. This gearbox feels pretty similar to the 911r’s box, and I’d imagine it’s mechanically close as well. 
  Chassis wise, this is the single biggest difference btw the 3 cars. The 991.2 feels the most “old school” to me of the lot…not a lot of steering input is needed and you get a smooth and sure footed response from the front wheels with the suspension dipping slightly and the rear following suit perfectly clearly. The 911r felt livelier and WAY more tail happy than the 991.2 does to me, which lead to more hooning and a little more unique experience but not necessarily a better one for a longer drive I’d imagine. The 992 gt chassis is a LEAGUE above the 991.2 in response and capability. The 992’s  suspension is significantly stiffer (not necessarily a benefit) but the front end turn in and near telepathic/race car steering is something I actually loved in my 992 overall. That car had a REAL relationship to a race car and this 991.2 feels like a hopped up street sportscar. However, as a daily…that’s not a bad thing at ALL and Im loving this thing! #porsche #gt3touring

Aside from the 992 Touring which I left completely alone, I almost always have my dealership take out the rake that many pre 992 911s come with and then take out another 5-6mm all around while throwing in a dash more neg camber (normally an extra .3-.5 ish degrees)  added with often a Salt Bae style over the elbow spritz’ of positive toe  just to give just a little more zest to the car’s on road mannerism. Additionally, the little adjustment just makes these cars look so 🤌 *smooch face* and I just can’t get enough of how this 991.2 Touring sits now. While it’s subtle, I just love this little tweak and you can see it from the before pictures following the first few shop pics shown. Looking forward to getting this car out this week and getting some quieter HAWK pads (happy to take other suggestions) thrown on as I was spoiled by my 992 Touring’s silent ceramic brakes 😂.
